post_text:
4th graders interviewing John Carwell, education associate at the Department of Education. This is just one of many guests who will be visiting as part of our school wide celebration of Black History Month.

This year, our fourth grade team has decided to give students the opportunity to meet, interview, and learn from members of our Delaware African-American community and to come to understand that black history is not just 100 years ago, or just the studying of George Washington Carver, but that it was yesterday, it is today, and it will be tomorrow.

Currently we have representatives from DSU, Washington College, the Department of Education, Dover City Council, United Way, local builders and business owners, and leaders of non-profits. We would love to add a scientist, engineer, author, historian in the mix, and we are open for other suggestions.

post_text:
Campus Community School partners with ASA Transportation to provide daily bus services for our students. ASA is seeking bus aides for the upcoming school year. This position will work both the morning and afternoon runs. The aides will provide support to the drivers to ensure the safety of the students. Upon hire, the candidate will be required to complete a 2 day Delaware Department of Education training for bus attendants. Previous experience is a plus. Please note: ASA Transportation will be the employer for this position (not Campus Community School).

If you are interested in applying for this position, please contact Carolin Lyon at carolin.lyon@ccs.k12.de.us or 302-736-0403 ext. 102

post_text:
Our Application Period Begins Today!!! On November 5 at 8:00a Campus Community School will begin accepting applications for the 2019/2020 school year. Families may apply online at campuscommunityschool.com or in person by visiting our office at 350 Pear Street in Dover. To be considered for our lottery, families must apply before January 9 at 11:59p. Any application received after that date will be placed on our waiting list. The best chance for parents to obtain a spot is to apply within the given application period as our waiting list reached new heights this year. If you would like to see our school in action
please contact our office and schedule a tour.

post_text:
The Visionary Youth Peace Art Exhibition at The Delaware Contemporary is open until Sunday, September 23. Come and see the inspiring, beautiful and visionary art and words of 500+ young artists from around Delaware while you can, including 2 of our very own CCS students:

Student Name: Kerra Watson
Title: Net Neutrality
Medium: acrylic paint
Grade: 8th grade
Artist Statement: My painting, ‚ÄúNet Neutrality‚Äù represents the issue and current debate regarding net neutrality, and the people‚Äôs reactions to the subject. To me (the artist) this topic is an example of what there should peace be of and what would happen to the users of the internet without it. That‚Äôs why I chose this topic because there should be peace‚Ä¶even on the World Wide Web.

Student Name: Neave Chapman
Title: Shades of Peace
Medium: Digital photo
Grade: 8th
Artist Statement: My photo represents peace throughout all people, and all people can have peace. The star means pride and happiness in everyone.

post_text: Would you like your child to be a part of amazing educational experience that is Campus Community School? We have a select number of openings for fourth grade students. Our waiting list grows longer and longer as the grade level increases. If your child would like to attend Campus Community's middle school, 4th grade is the time to enter. As Campus Community Families know, openings within our school are rare, so this is your opportunity. Is your child in another grade level? You can still apply to our school. Although we do have waiting lists, things change quickly over the summer. Contact our office now at 302-736-0403.

post_text: Yesterday our 7th grade students visited the Holocaust Museum in Washington D.C. They were able to view the interpretation and documentation of the Holocaust provided by the museum and solidify what they discussed in class during their Anne Frank lesson. The trip was a very eye opening and moving experience for students and staff. The group also visited the WWII Memorial and the Korean War Memorial. #holocaustmuseum #washingtondc #wwiimemorial #koreanwarmemorial

post_text:
Do you want the chance to help a real-life super hero? On Saturday, April 28 at 9:00a Campus Community School will host the "Cougars for a Cause 5k for Ben Knapp." This will take place just before our PTO Sponsored Spring Fair. Ben is a former Campus Community Student that suddenly and unexpectedly experienced a traumatic brain injury on Oct. 21, 2011 that left him blind, unable to speak and barely able to move. Ben has gone on to accomplish amazing things, including graduating from high school. Ben's family raises money to assist with his continually increasing medical costs. You can contribute in a number of ways. You can simply run the race, become a sponsor, or be a "silent hero". You can donate to Ben at https://www.gofundme.com/22jn3wfg
If you would like to learn more about Ben Knapp, see his story at
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lcnNPh1ugEw&t=22s
or watch the story that WBOC had on Ben at
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mr281b0bdBU
